    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-07T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-07T23:00:00-05:00" n="845"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d845">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.1111Sh4/–: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi>, (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-08T12:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 8, 1920—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received 9:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. A. L. Shelton, missionary doctor, Foreign Christian Missionary Society,
                    kidnaped by brigands January 3rd, traveling Batang to Yunnanfu, two days journey
                    from the latter place. Reported held for ransom. Wife and two daughters safe.
                    Further details <pb facs="0892" n="794" xml:id="pg_794"/> lacking. Have
                    requested cooperation of French consul, Yunnanfu, and have telegraphed to local
                    governor. Will keep the Department fully informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tenney</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
